2. Prepare the data

#remove temp <-17
met <- met[temp > -17][elev == 9999.0, elev := NA]
library(lubridate)

Attaching package: 'lubridate'
The following objects are masked from 'package:base':

    date, intersect, setdiff, union
met[, week := week(as.Date(paste(year, month, day, sep ="-")))]
met <- met[week == min(week, na.rm=TRUE)]
met_avg <- met[,.(temp=mean(temp,na.rm=TRUE), rh=mean(rh, na.rm=TRUE),
                  wind.sp=mean(wind.sp,na.rm=TRUE),
                  vis.dist=mean(vis.dist,na.rm=TRUE),
                  dew.point=mean(dew.point,na.rm=TRUE),
                  lat=mean(lat), lon=mean(lon),
                  elev=mean(elev,na.rm=TRUE)), by="USAFID"]
met_avg$region <- ifelse(met_avg$lon > -98 & met_avg$lat > 39.71, "north east",
                         ifelse(met_avg$lon > -98 &
                                  met_avg$lat < 39.71, "south east",
                                ifelse(met_avg$lon < -98 & met_avg$lat > 39.71,
                                       "north west", "south west")))
#create categorical variable
met_avg$elev_cat <- ifelse(met_avg$elev > 252, "high", "low")
table(met_avg$region)

       484        146        649        296

The northeast has the greatest variability with some high wind speed outliers, while the northwest displays a more uniform and moderate range. The southeast is more concentrated around typical values with limited extremes, and the southwest shows a balanced spread without very high outliers. Overall, the northeast stands out for its wider distribution.

The plot shows weak association between dew point and wind speed. In the northeast and southeast, wind speeds remain fairly consistent regardless of dew point, though the southeast shows slightly higher variation at higher dew points. The northwest and southwest also display flat trends, with wind speeds mostly clustered at lower values.

7.

library(leaflet)
met_avg2 <- met_avg[!is.na(rh)]

top10 <- met_avg2[rank(-rh) <= 10]

rh_pal = colorNumeric(c('blue', 'purple', 'red'), domain=met_avg2$rh)

leaflet(met_avg2) %>%
  addProviderTiles("OpenStreetMap") %>%
  addCircles(lat=~lat, lng=~lon, color=~rh_pal(rh),
             label=~paste0(round(rh,2), 'rh'), opacity=1, radius=500) %>%
  addMarkers(lat=~lat, lng=~lon, label=~paste0(round(rh,2), 'rh'), data=top10) %>%
  addLegend('bottomleft', pal=rh_pal, values=met_avg2$rh,
            title="Relative Humidity", opacity=1)

From the graph it shows that the closer you are you a body of water the more humid it is.
